{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17515845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17515845"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:35:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:35:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12503"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12503"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.03,0.13,0.84,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5009"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115563"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5009"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12503"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97566"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2080"},{"type":"tags","id":"2932"},{"type":"tags","id":"3514"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"6364"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8300"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8658"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14104"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39257"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42769"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43336"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49235"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115563"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 33-year-old woman presents to the antenatal clinic at 28 weeks\u0027 gestation for routine review. She reports increased appetite and thirst over the past few weeks but denies headaches or visual changes. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She has no family history of diabetes and her pre-pregnancy BMI was 22 kg/m\u00b2. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. A 75g oral glucose tolerance test has been performed with the following results:\u003Cbr /\u003EFasting glucose: 5.7 mmol/L (\u0026lt; 5.3)\u003Cbr /\u003EOne-hour post-glucose load: 10.4 mmol/L (\u0026lt; 10.6)\u003Cbr /\u003ETwo-hour post-glucose load: 8.1 mmol/L (\u0026lt; 11.1)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Type 1 diabetes mellitus","Type 2 diabetes mellitus","Normal glucose tolerance","Gestational diabetes mellitus","Latent autoimmune diabetes in adults"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms of hyperglycaemia during pregnancy and has undergone a 75g oral glucose tolerance test at 28 weeks\u0027 gestation. According to the 2025 ADIPS consensus recommendations, \u003Cstrong\u003Egestational diabetes mellitus\u003C/strong\u003E is diagnosed when any one of the following thresholds is met: \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Efasting plasma glucose \u2265\u20095.3\u20136.9\u2009mmol/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E1\u2010hour plasma glucose\u2009\u2265\u200910.6 mmol/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E2-hour plasma glucose\u2009\u2265\u20099.0\u201311.0\u2009mmol/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the fasting glucose of 5.7 is abnormal and diagnostic of gestational diabetes mellitus. Gestational diabetes mellitus accounts for the vast majority of diabetes in pregnancy cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal glucose tolerance\u003C/strong\u003E would require all three values to be below the diagnostic thresholds.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 1 diabetes mellitus\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents in younger individuals with a rapid onset of symptoms, often with ketosis, and is characterised by autoimmune destruction of pancreatic beta cells. The clinical presentation and timing during pregnancy make gestational diabetes more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 2 diabetes mellitus\u003C/strong\u003E is more commonly associated with obesity, metabolic syndrome, and a family history of diabetes. This patient\u0027s normal pre-pregnancy BMI and absence of risk factors, combined with the timing of diagnosis during pregnancy, favour gestational diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELatent autoimmune diabetes in adults\u003C/strong\u003E is a slowly progressive form of autoimmune diabetes diagnosed in those 30 years or older with positive autoantibodies to islet \u03b2 cells and insulin dependence for at least the initial 6 months after diagnosis. It is not typically diagnosed during pregnancy using routine OGTT screening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGestational diabetes develops due to insulin resistance caused by placental hormones, particularly human placental lactogen. Most cases resolve after delivery, but women remain at increased risk of developing type 2 diabetes later in life. Postpartum glucose testing at 6-12 weeks is required to exclude type 2 diabetes mellitus.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gestational diabetes mellitus is diagnosed using the 75g oral glucose tolerance test with updated 2025 ADIPS consensus recommendations","A single abnormal value on the OGTT is sufficient to diagnose gestational diabetes mellitus.","Gestational diabetes typically develops in the second or third trimester due to placental hormones causing insulin resistance."],"references":["ADIPS consensus guidelines for the testing and diagnosis of ... (no date). Available at: http://www.adips.org/downloads/2014ADIPSGDMGuidelinesV18.11.2014_000.pdf (Accessed: March 30, 2023).","Nankervis, A., Price, S. and Conn, J. (2018) \u201cGestational diabetes mellitus: A pragmatic approach to diagnosis and management,\u201d Australian Journal of General Practice, 47(7), pp. 445\u2013449. Available at: https://doi.org/10.31128/ajgp-01-18-4479.","Conn, J. (2018) \u201cChapter 12: Type 2 diabetes prevention and early detection,\u201d Australian Journal of General Practice, 47(7), pp. 445\u2013449. Available at: https://doi.org/10.31128/ajgp-01-18-4479.","Meloncelli, N. et al. (2018) \u201cDiagnosis and management practices for gestational diabetes mellitus in Australia: Cross\u2010sectional survey of the multidisciplinary team,\u201d Australian and New Zealand Journal of Obstetrics and Gynaecology, 59(2), pp. 208\u2013214. Available at: https://doi.org/10.1111/ajo.12816.","Rajkumar V, Levine SN. Latent Autoimmune Diabetes. [Updated 2022 Jun 21]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557897/","Kreider, K.E. (2019) \u201cThe diagnosis and management of atypical types of diabetes,\u201d The Journal for Nurse Practitioners, 15(2). Available at: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.nurpra.2018.09.022.","Sweeting, A, Hare, MJ, de Jersey, SJ, Shub, AL, Zinga, J, Foged, C, Hall, RM, Wong, T \u0026 Simmons, D 2025, \u2018Australasian Diabetes in Pregnancy Society (ADIPS) 2025 consensus recommendations for the screening, diagnosis and classification of gestational diabetes\u2019, Medical Journal of Australia, Wiley, viewed 23 June 2025, \u003Chttps://www.mja.com.au/journal/2025/223/3/australasian-diabetes-pregnancy-society-adips-2025-consensus-recommendations\u003E."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97566"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12503"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97566","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97566"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-24T13:13:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-24T13:15:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5009"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115563"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synon